0:["LJgHqRHEXtboNpof0740S",[[["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","history-of-latitude-and-longitude","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__?{\"slug\":\"history-of-latitude-and-longitude\"}",{}]}]}]},"$undefined","$undefined",true],["",{"children":["blog",{"children":[["slug","history-of-latitude-and-longitude","d"],{"children":["__PAGE__",{},[["$L1",[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BlogPosting\",\"headline\":\"The history of latitude and longitude — from sextants to satellites\",\"description\":\"How a Greek scholar, a Yorkshire clockmaker, and a global voting conference in 1884 produced the two numbers your phone shows you today.\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-06-01\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-06-01\",\"author\":{\"@type\":\"Person\",\"name\":\"Ahmed Anwar\"},\"publisher\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"GetMyLocations\",\"logo\":{\"@type\":\"ImageObject\",\"url\":\"https://getmylocations.com/icon-512.png\"}},\"mainEntityOfPage\":{\"@type\":\"WebPage\",\"@id\":\"https://getmylocations.com/blog/history-of-latitude-and-longitude\"}}"}}],["$","main",null,{"role":"main","className":"max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 py-12","children":[["$","nav",null,{"aria-label":"Breadcrumb","className":"text-xs text-slate-400 mb-4","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-electric-400","children":"Home"}],["$","span",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","className":"mx-1.5","children":"/"}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"hover:text-electric-400","children":"Blog"}]]}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"font-display text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight leading-tight","children":"The history of latitude and longitude — from sextants to satellites"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-4 flex items-center gap-3 flex-wrap","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-center gap-2.5","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"w-9 h-9 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-electric-400 to-electric-600 grid place-items-center text-ink-950 font-bold text-sm","aria-hidden":"true","children":"A"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"text-sm leading-tight","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"font-semibold text-slate-100","children":"Ahmed Anwar"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-400","children":[["$","time",null,{"dateTime":"2026-06-01","children":"June 1, 2026"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5","aria-hidden":"true","children":"·"}],["$","span",null,{"children":[7," min read"]}]]}]]}]]}],["$","ul",null,{"className":"flex gap-1.5 ml-auto","children":[["$","li","history",{"className":"px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full bg-white/5 ring-1 ring-white/10 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-300","children":"history"}],["$","li","coordinates",{"className":"px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full bg-white/5 ring-1 ring-white/10 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-300","children":"coordinates"}],["$","li","gps",{"className":"px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full bg-white/5 ring-1 ring-white/10 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-slate-300","children":"gps"}]]}]]}],["$","hr",null,{"className":"my-8 border-white/10"}],["$","article",null,{"className":"prose-invert","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"In October 1884, twenty-five countries sat down in a conference room in Washington and voted on which line should count as the middle of the world. France lost the vote, abstained from the result, and kept the Paris meridian on its own charts for another twenty-seven years out of pride. That argument is the reason your phone today reads longitude from a brass strip set into the ground at a south-east London observatory."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-4 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Latitude was never really in dispute — the equator picks itself, sitting halfway between the poles because that’s where the planet’s own spin tells you it should. Longitude had no such natural anchor, which is why the political fight took so long. What I find genuinely surprising about the history is how recently the system settled. The grid is 2,200 years old, but the version of it your phone actually uses was finalised within the last 50."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"The Greeks drew the first grid"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Around 230 BC the Greek scholar Eratosthenes — the same man who calculated the size of the Earth by watching shadows in two cities — sketched the first coordinate system on a map of the known world. He drew lines parallel to the equator and lines running pole to pole. A century later Hipparchus formalised them as 360 degrees and proposed using astronomical observations to actually assign coordinates to specific places."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["By 150 AD, Ptolemy’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Geography"}]," listed about eight thousand places with their latitude and longitude. He got the size of the Mediterranean wrong by 40%, but the framework is unmistakable. If you put a Ptolemaic coordinate next to a modern one for the same city, the format is exactly the same."]}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"Latitude was the easy half"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Finding how far north or south you are turns out to be straightforward if you can see the stars. The angle the sun sits above the horizon at noon, or the angle of the North Star above your spot in the northern hemisphere, gives you latitude directly. The instruments — the astrolabe, then the sextant — got better over the centuries but the principle never changed. Any decent ship’s captain in the 1700s could read latitude reliably from the deck of a moving ship."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"Longitude was the disaster that killed people"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"Longitude requires you to know the time. If it is noon where you are — which the sun tells you — and it is, say, 4 PM at Greenwich, then the four-hour difference tells you how far east or west of Greenwich you are. The catch is that there were no clocks accurate enough to keep Greenwich time on a ship that had been at sea for weeks. Pendulum clocks were useless on a rolling deck. The astronomical alternatives were complex, slow, and only worked at night in clear weather."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The result was a regular slaughter at sea. Ships missed their islands by hundreds of miles and ran aground. In 1707 a British fleet wrecked itself on the rocks of the Isles of Scilly because the navigators had no idea how far east they were; nearly 2,000 sailors drowned in one night. Seven years later, in 1714, Parliament passed the Longitude Act, putting up what was then a colossal cash prize — £20,000, the equivalent of millions today — for a workable solution."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"John Harrison’s clocks"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"John Harrison was a Yorkshire carpenter who taught himself clockmaking. Over forty years he built a series of marine chronometers — the first portable clocks accurate enough to keep Greenwich time on a wooden ship in a North Atlantic gale. His fourth attempt, H4, ran for 81 days at sea and lost less than five seconds. Longitude was solved. The Royal Navy still owed him most of the prize money for decades afterwards; he had to petition the king personally to get it."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"All four of Harrison’s clocks still work and are on display at the Royal Observatory in Greenwich today. H4 is the size of a large pocket watch."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"Whose meridian is zero?"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"With reliable clocks, every seafaring nation could measure longitude from somewhere. The French ran theirs through Paris. The Spanish through Cadiz. Americans through Washington. The Portuguese through Lisbon. Each country’s charts were unreadable on another country’s ships, and that became expensive once steamships and international cabling made commerce continuous."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The 1884 Washington conference settled it. Greenwich won — not because it was geographically special, but because British nautical charts were already the most widely used and reprinting every chart in the world was unappealing. France abstained out of pique and France’s civil railway clocks ran on “Paris time minus nine minutes 21 seconds” (the offset from Greenwich) until 1911, when they finally gave in."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"From sextants to satellites"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"The instruments changed entirely; the coordinate system did not. GPS, launched by the US Department of Defense in the late 1970s and made fully available for civilian use in 2000, gives you latitude and longitude using exactly the definition Ptolemy used, accurate to a few meters instead of a few miles. The Galileo (EU), GLONASS (Russia), and BeiDou (China) systems all use the same grid. Your phone reads from all of them simultaneously and hands the result to whichever app asked for it."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":"What I think is worth pausing on: a Greek scholar in Alexandria, an English clockmaker in Yorkshire, and twenty-five governments arguing in Washington all contributed to the number your weather app needs to forecast for the right city. None of them could have imagined any of the others. That is the part of the history I keep coming back to."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"font-display text-2xl font-bold mt-12","children":"See your own coordinates"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed","children":["Two clicks on the"," ",["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/gps-coordinates","className":"text-electric-400 hover:underline font-semibold","children":"GPS Coordinates tool"}]," ","give you the latitude and longitude that took two millennia to make readable. The latitude number you see comes from astronomical principles a Greek scholar would have recognised; the longitude number comes from a Yorkshire clock and an 1884 vote."]}]]}],["$","aside",null,{"aria-label":"About the author","className":"mt-14 not-prose rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-6 sm:p-7","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"flex items-start gap-4","children":[["$","div",null,{"aria-hidden":"true","className":"shrink-0 w-12 h-12 rounded-full bg-gradient-to-br from-electric-400 to-electric-600 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-ink-950","children":"AA"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"min-w-0","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.16em] text-electric-400 font-semibold","children":"Written by"}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-display text-lg font-bold text-slate-100 mt-1","children":"Ahmed Anwar"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-slate-300/90 leading-relaxed mt-2","children":"Independent web developer in Karachi. Builds the geolocation tools, mapping pages, and coordinate utilities on GetMyLocations. Writes about GPS, browser geolocation, and IP geolocation from the perspective of someone who ships the code, not the marketing."}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-slate-400 mt-3 leading-relaxe